<bioghist altrender="historyhy" encodinganalog="545" id="a2">
<head>Historical Note</head>
<p>
The State Water Commission was established in 1925 by Public Acts chpt. 143. Its function was to determine through hearing if "any person, fir, or corporation is polluting the waters of the state" and if finding that to be the case then it "may make an order directing such person, firm or corporation 
to use or to operate some practicable and reasonably available system or means which will reduce, control or eliminate such pollution having regard for the rights and interests of all persons concerned, provided the cost of installation, maintenance and operation thereof shall not be unreasonable or inequitable."
On June 1, 1957, the State Water Commission merged with the State Flood Control and water Policy Commission and the State Board of Supervision of Dams to form the Water Resources Commission. The new Commission's purpose was to "study the water resources of the State and the present laws pertaining thereto. It shall further 
study the relative needs of the various groups represented on said commission with particular reference to the greatest good to the people."
In 1971 the Water Resources Commission merged into the new Department of Environmental Protection.
</p>

<p>
See also the <extptr linktype="simple" href="http://www.cslib.org/agencies/waterresourcescommission.htm" show="replace" actuate="onrequest" title="Water Resources Commission Agency History"/>.
</p> 

</bioghist>

<scopecontent encodinganalog="520" id="a3">
<head>Scope and Content</head>
<p>
Includes minutes of both the State Water Commission and the Water Resources Commission, 1925-1971; some biennial reports, 1938-1940; 
and some miscellaneous material that post-date the merge into the Department of Environmental Protection, most concerning the Insfrasturcture Task Force, 1983-1984.
</p>
</scopecontent>

